x4freetext: Details of
experiments.
Last checking has been done.
A set of nine stacks containing the following targets-
polyethylene, Al, Cu, Ag and Pb.  The target had a
thickness of about 10% of the interaction mean free
path of the beam particles.  This value was found to be
a good compromise to maximize the number of projectile
fragments produced inside the target without generating
too many reinteractions of these fragments  inside  the
target.
Track positions on CR-39 foils as well as their track
area and shape of the etch figures were determined by
completely automated measurements. They were performed
with scanning system based on computer controlled
microscope stage and image analysis techniques.
The cross sections are derived from the number of
particles with different charges counted up- and
down-stream the target.  Since one has to count the
number of fragments produced inside the target by the
interaction of a well defined number of incoming
particles, the number of projictiles and fragments has
to be counter in congruent areas.  Between 80% and 90%
of all tracks could be reconstructed through the thick
targets.  Some  of these tracks were used to determine
the congruent areas on the last foil side in the front
and the first foil side in the back stack.
CR-39 plastic nuclear track detectors-
in experiments was used stacks with 5 detector foils
upstream and 12 detector foils downstream a target.
Each detector foil had a thickness of about
640-micrometers. By using stacks of Cr-39 foils, it is
possible to determine the trajectories and the charges
of the projectiles ions and their fragments.
The authors get charge resolutions between 0.1 and 0.12
elementary gharge for fragments charge numbers from 6
upto 13.
